5 Tips to Survive your Technical Interviewâš¡ï¸
Practice.
It sounds really silly and obvious, but practice not only coding new problems but also explaining them out loud. The more you practice coding, verbalizing your thought process, and explaining what youâ€™re doing, the more natural itâ€™ll feel when you do the real interview. Hereâ€™s a few places you can practice your coding skills:
Big SQL Energy Intermediate Course ðŸ”— [ https://substack.com/redirect/bbda282b-d433-4d04-a59b-4448b106557a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]

Leetcode [ https://substack.com/redirect/e9025b19-4a5f-4e6c-a00f-b2a804fb7ec2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]ðŸ”—
HackerRank [ https://substack.com/redirect/2cb113d0-4fc4-4c5e-919e-04e1f8de8f40?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]ðŸ”—
Your own IDE, I use DBeaver [ https://substack.com/redirect/6cd4f9ac-7245-4cdc-a8eb-176c53a1fbb4?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]ðŸ”— for SQL & Jupyter Notebooks in Anaconda [ https://substack.com/redirect/b2a57b63-6e53-4e78-9ff7-07c83c5588f7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]ðŸ”— for Python
Real Interviewsâ€” the best way to really practice is to do real live coding interviews! Itâ€™s okay if they donâ€™t go as planned. Learn, iterate, and try again!
Communicate.
Verbalize everything you do and why. Technical interviews arenâ€™t JUST to assess your coding skills. Theyâ€™re also to see how well you understand what youâ€™re doing and can communicate it. Never stay silent in a coding interview! Make sure youâ€™re walking the interviewer through all of your decisions and thoughts. This also ensures that youâ€™re on the right path and gives them a chance to intervene if needed.
Ex. â€œNow Iâ€™m going to do a LEFT join here so I donâ€™t filter out any rows of the X table that donâ€™t have a match in the Y table.â€
Ask Questions.
Yes, youâ€™re expected to ask questions and not just pump out code like a robot (or should I say like ChatGPTðŸ˜‰). Asking questions shows the interviewer how you think and collaborate. Do you jump right in and start coding or do you ask clarifying questions to make sure you really understand the problem and data? The second will help you stand out. Asking questions is also a great way for YOU to interview THEM! You want to see how they respond to questions and answer them. If theyâ€™re not willing to, they probably wonâ€™t be great to work with, and it may be a red flag!
Ex. â€œIs this the primary key of the table? Can I assume all IDs in X table are also in Y table? Where did this data come from?â€
Address any limitations, assumptions, or next steps.
Address any limitations you see in the data or problem, any assumptions youâ€™re making about the company or data, and any next steps youâ€™d love to be able to take if you were offered the positionðŸ˜‰ This is deeper-level thinking that shows that you can solve problems without ignoring important details. It also shows that youâ€™re able to iterate and think about how to improve the work in the future! I always think about these 3 things every time I do a coding interview or take home assignment.
Limitation Ex: â€œI noticed that weâ€™re not able to track column X for anonymous users, so weâ€™ll have to note that in the final analysis.â€
Assumption Ex: â€œIâ€™m assuming that all products follow the same payment workflow. Let me know if thatâ€™s incorrect.â€
Next Steps Ex: â€œIf I were to continue on this project in this role, Iâ€™d love to use wildcards to determine the most popular website pages using the URLs.â€
Always point back to the Business!
When working through a live coding problem, think about the business domain. What business question are you trying to answer and why does it matter? Show that youâ€™re thinking about the business impact and not just about solving that one problem. If youâ€™re not sure, ask about it! Asking questions goes a long way. When you get the final answer provide your thoughts and what you might recommend to the business or team. Many people forget to include business skills in their interviews.
Ex. â€œSince most subscriptions originate from a free trial, Iâ€™d definitely start to look into why this is and perhaps reduce friction to start free trials. This would help us encourage more trial starts!â€
Technical interviews (and take home assignments) can be really daunting and even traumatic if they donâ€™t go well. (Hey, Iâ€™ve been there too!) But I promise you can do it! It just takes lots of practice and confidence-building. Use these 5 tips to be best prepared and stand out!

The End of the Dashboard Analyst ðŸª¦
A few years ago, you could get hired as a data analyst just by dragging a few charts into a Tableau dashboard, tossing in a few vague KPIs, and calling it a day.
The pipelines mightâ€™ve been broken half of the time. 
The filters didnâ€™t always work. 
There were probably errors in the data.
But it didnâ€™t matter, because companies were so desperate to â€œbecome data-driven,â€ theyâ€™d take anything that looked like insight. They wanted to say they were data-driven and feel data-driven more than they actually wanted to be data-driven.
Data was sexy, cool, and new. (ok fine, data wasnâ€™t newâ€¦ itâ€™s been around a long time. But the way companies were suddenly prioritizing it more and demanding an increase in data talent was new.)
But weâ€™re not in 2020 anymore. Itâ€™s 2025 now, and things have changed already in only 5 years. Heck, itâ€™s only been a couple of years since ChatGPT launched and see how much has changed even since then! ðŸ˜…
We have to grow and evolve as data analysts to stay relevant in this ever-changing industryâ€¦ especially if we want to compete with AI. Anyone (literally anyone with thumbs) can use AI to spin up a decent-looking dashboard in seconds now. Stakeholders. Interns. Product managers. Even executives ðŸ˜‚
So if your biggest skill is building dashboards: youâ€™re already replaceable.
Letâ€™s be real: the analysts who will actually stay relevant (and get the best jobs, the biggest raises, and the most respect)â€¦ are the ones who can do way more than just build visuals.
Companies arenâ€™t hiring dashboard monkeys anymore. Theyâ€™re hiring business translators, strategic thinkers, and full-stack data professionals. The bar is higher now, and thatâ€™s a good thing because it means improved analytics and insights across the industry.
Hereâ€™s what actually makes you valuable as a data analyst in 2025 and beyond:
âœ¨ Translate business questions into code & analyses 
âœ¨ Manage stakeholders, expectations, & scope 
âœ¨ Build semantic views to support reporting 
âœ¨ Maintain and QA legacy code 
âœ¨ ETL data sources like CRMs
Because hereâ€™s the truth no one wants to say: AI isnâ€™t replacing data analysts. Itâ€™s just exposing the ones who were never doing much to begin with ðŸ˜‚ (sorry if this hurts your feelings)
So if youâ€™ve been building your technical skills, asking better business questions, and learning how to own the full data lifecycle? Good. Youâ€™re ahead of the curve. If not, nowâ€™s the time to level up.

column7: 7 Real-World Lessons from Data Leaders at LinkedIn, Dropbox & More
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/7-real-world-lessons-from-data-leaders

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here ðŸ‘‹
A few weeks back, I hosted two weeks of webinars for data leaders. We covered topics like communication with the business, driving impact, and say no, etc. Below, youâ€™ll find seven of the webinars with data leaders from companies like LinkedIn, Dropbox, and more!
Before we dive into the article, Iâ€™m also excited to share that Iâ€™ll be running the second cohort of the Data Leaders Playbook Accelerator. This six-week program is focused on helping data leaders drive more impact and play a larger strategic role in their company. If youâ€™re interested, you can sign up for the program here. [ https://substack.com/redirect/38b5dbd8-0c81-421d-b881-5eb2c38c5ed2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
With that out of the way, letâ€™s jump into it!
Intro
Over the past few years, Iâ€™ve spoken with dozens of data leaders who were recently promoted.
Many had to spend time honing an entirely new set of skills while juggling some level of delivering on technical projects.
Others were suddenly being asked to make decisions on technologies that would impact their companies for years to come, often without being able to ask anyone else for help. Thatâ€™s why, over the past few weeks, I have been hosting webinars asking data leaders from companies like LinkedIn, Dropbox, Carhartt, and several consultants to share their experiences.
These webinars focused on frameworks for better communication and on understanding the business better. They also explored several technologies so you can make better decisions about what to use for your team.
So, letâ€™s explore these seven webinars, which you should watch if you want to take your data team to the next level.
1) Frameworks Data Leader and ICs Should Know to Maximize Their Impact by Tessa Xie
Many data teams struggle to communicate [ https://substack.com/redirect/7cd915b8-5f67-4366-ac32-603edf618ccb?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] clearly to the business, whether it be results from an analysis or requesting a budget for new tooling.
If you want to communicate information to business leaders  [ https://substack.com/redirect/76fa44a3-1eab-4204-adce-4f9ecc072abb?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]or drive impact, having several frameworks underneath your tool belt will be helpful. Thatâ€™s where Tessa Xie  â€˜s webinar on four frameworks you can use as a data leader will be useful!
She covers several methods you can use to better break down messaging and deliver results that will allow the business to get up to speed quickly.
2) Why Data Teams Fail By Shachar Meir 
Last year I spoke with several business leaders who were frustrated with their data teams  [ https://substack.com/redirect/2c64169c-461b-425d-9c83-68eb7a054ce2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]and felt they werenâ€™t delivering the hoped-for value. They were failing. Shachar Meir [ https://substack.com/redirect/6737fde1-d182-49a4-b0cc-94fd5a4fb6a0?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] has been leading data teams at companies like Facebook and PayPal and helping them turn around when they might be struggling.
This webinar will cover several methods you can use to help keep your data team from failing.
3) Saying No And Other Difficult Conversations For Data Leaders By Aaron Wilkerson
An important skill youâ€™ll need to learn as a data leader is the ability to say no. This skill is hard for many data ICs and leaders to pick up. After all, it's far easier to just say yes right? 
I asked Aaron Wilkerson  to share his thoughts on saying no and having other difficult conversations as a data leader.
Because you canâ€™t just say no, you need your business partners and stakeholders on the same page as you. They need to understand what the cost of you saying yes is and what the value of you protecting your teams time provides.
4) How To Balance Long Term Projects and Ad Hoc Work As A Data Leader By Lauren Lin
One of the challenges all data teams face is balancing ad-hoc data requests with long-term projects. After all, you have to ensure your leadership believes you can deliver and gets timely information, but you also need to build a lasting data infrastructure. Sometimes, these can be at odds.
The The Tension of Orthodoxy and Speed [ https://substack.com/redirect/42b77164-7677-4418-9e8e-63919a74c916?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], as Joe Reis  put it.
In this webinar Lauren Lin [ https://substack.com/redirect/25ae729a-11b3-4e50-ab78-5becad9c45df?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] will share her methods for balancing ad-hoc requests and long term projects.
SeattleDataGuyâ€™s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Picking Tools And Managing Your Data Stack
For the next few videos I wanted to focus more on tools and solutions data teams  [ https://substack.com/redirect/2c64169c-461b-425d-9c83-68eb7a054ce2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]use.
Now tools and solutions do not solve problems on their own. But they can help make your day to day workflows considerably easier. Thatâ€™s why I asked several of the speakers to talk on their experience with different tools like Snowflake [ https://substack.com/redirect/7cb31570-aea5-480a-91d6-ac5d133a77d2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], Databricks [ https://substack.com/redirect/071f0fa8-53fe-47c7-a4d4-f02b66e2db09?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and dbt.
Letâ€™s dive into the next three videos.
5) What You Need To Know Before You Use Snowflake By Jeff Skoldberg
Back in 2023 an article went viral in the data world titled â€œI Accidentally Saved Half A Million Dollars [ https://substack.com/redirect/d3ffea04-844a-4385-b2cb-0c68dd8ffa2c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]â€. The focus of the article was about how a data professional made a small adjustment to their Snowflake instance and saved 500k. 
But there are many other adjustments you can make to reduce your Snowflake bill and just good practice to follow that you might not be told by your account executive. Thatâ€™s where Jeff Skoldberg [ https://substack.com/redirect/8c467dea-82d1-4460-9c3e-b2ffaee8ba3d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]â€™s webinar comes in.
Heâ€™ll share his thoughts on what you should know before you use Snowflake.
6) What You Need To Know Before You Use Databricks By Josue Bogran
If you go on Linkedin, then perhaps youâ€™ve seen content from Josue Bogran [ https://substack.com/redirect/0cb077be-ae23-4dcb-945f-e9b91c743d22?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. He has spoken a lot about Databricks and other tools, so I asked him what people should know before they push play on Databricks.
So if you want to learn more about what to expect, you should check out this webinar.
7) dbt vs SQLMesh By Yuki Kakegawa
With all the movement in the data world, whether it be acquisitions, new funding rounds, and so forth, I wanted to have Yuki  share his experiences with dbt and SQLMesh. 
He has been working with a whole list of tools recently, and so I wanted him to share what he has found is the difference between dbt [ https://substack.com/redirect/d7d1d05c-2512-4faf-b715-45bd4f2d4972?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and SQLMesh [ https://substack.com/redirect/aec09c1a-0839-4826-ba07-c307167c2c9c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Final Thoughts
As a data leader, youâ€™ll need to learn many new skills [ https://substack.com/redirect/08495743-00c7-48f6-b260-94755a2f78ea?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. For example, youâ€™ll need to learn how to plan your data roadmap, grow your team, or improve stakeholder relations. If these skills are new to you or youâ€™re just looking to improve them, then I know the videos above were helpful.
Thank you to everyone who led these webinars, and as always, thanks for reading!
The Data Leaderâ€™s Playbook Accelerator: Build Trust, Navigate Vendors, and Deliver Impact
Over the past few years, I have led dozens of data team turnarounds, set up infrastructure for companies ranging from small start-ups to large billion-dollar organizations, and coached new data leaders on how to handle tough stakeholders.
Now, I wanted to condense all of that into a 6-week program that would help you be better prepared for dealing with issues such as:
Building trust with stakeholders
Picking the right tools while navigating aggressive sales tactics
Negotiating with vendors
Juggling ad-hoc business requests with long-term strategic planning
Dealing with a lot of hype around AI and real-time
Balancing their technical expertise while also having to lead
And more

Bufstream: Stream Kafka Messages to Iceberg Tables in Minutes
By VuTrinh.  
Fourteen years ago, a team led by Jay Kreps built Kafka to meet LinkedIn's growing log processing demands. Since its open-source release, Kafka has become the de facto standard for distributed messaging.
But hereâ€™s the catch: Kafkaâ€™s design isnâ€™t optimized for the cloud era. Compute and storage canâ€™t scale independently, cross-availability-zone transfer fees due to data replication, and other challenges persist whether you run Kafka locally or in the cloud.

Bite-sized AI news, fresh daily






p0 Microsoft Panic-Buys $17.4B Worth of GPU Infrastructure

 * Nebius Group's stock exploded 40% after Microsoft basically said "take my money" for a five-year AI data center deal worth
   $17.4 billion.

 * When you're so desperate for compute that you throw $17B at a company most people can't pronounce, the GPU shortage is very
   real (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/nebius-jumps-174-billion-ai-computing-deal-with-microsoft-2025-09-09/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p! Big on AI? Not Big on Spending?

 * Galaxy.ai is the world's #1 AI platform with 3000+ AI tools (everythingbfrom text to video) at one place for just $15/mo

 * p, ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, Grok, Llama, Perplexity, DeepSeek

 * p( Midjourney, Ideogram, Leonardo, Stable Diffusion, DALLB7E 3, Flux, Nano Banana, GPT-Image

 * p, Veo 3, Luma, Kling, Pika, HeyGen, RunwayML, Hailuo (Minimax)

 * p5 ElevenLabs, Lyria, Hedra, CassetteAI

 * p Works seamlessly on web, iOS, and Android

 * p	 Join millions who have switched to Galaxy.ai [https://galaxy.ai]




p Cognition AI Somehow Worth $10.2B Despite Laying People Off

 * The makers of Devin (the AI that codes better than your junior dev) just raised $400M, jumping from $4B to $10.2B valuation
   faster than their bot can debug Python.

 * VCs are betting that AI will replace programmers while simultaneously funding the programmers building the AI. The irony is not
   lost on us. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/08/cognition-ai-defies-turbulence-with-a-400m-raise-at-10-2b-valuation/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p Databricks Hits $100B Valuation by Actually Making Money

 * Data analytics giant Databricks closed a $1B round at $100B valuation, projecting $4B in revenue because 15,000+ companies need
   somewhere to dump their data and call it "AI-ready."

 * Turns out the real money isn't in building ChatGPT clones b it's in selling shovels during the AI gold rush (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/databricks-projects-4-billion-annualized-revenue-surging-ai-demand-2025-09-08/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p OpenAI Threatens to Leave California Over Profit Drama

 * Reports suggest OpenAI execs are eyeing an exit from California because the state's AG is investigating their plan to ditch the
   "non-profit" part of their identity.

 * When your $19B funding depends on convincing regulators you're still the good guys, maybe don't threaten to rage-quit the state
   (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/08/openai-denies-that-its-weighing-a-last-ditch-california-exit-amid-regulatory-pressure-over-its-restructuring/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p Volkswagen Discovers AI, Plans to Spend b,1B by 2030

 * VW announced they'll invest up to one billion euros in AI by 2030, because apparently making cars wasn't complicated enough
   already.

 * Legacy automakers are finally realizing that Tesla's secret sauce wasn't just batteries and cult-like marketing b it was
   software. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/volkswagen-invest-up-billion-euros-ai-by-end-decade-2025-09-09/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p Anthropic Actually Wants AI Regulation (Plot Twist)

 * Claude's creators officially endorsed California's SB 53 safety bill, making them the first major AI lab to say "please
   regulate us before we accidentally end the world."

 * When the company obsessed with AI safety asks for government oversight, maybe we should listen (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/08/anthropic-endorses-californias-ai-safety-bill-sb-53/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p Europe Throws b,600M at Data Centers Because AI Needs to Live Somewhere

 * Swedish company EcoDataCenter secured 600 million euros from Deutsche Bank to build more AI data centers, because GPUs need
   homes too.

 * The AI revolution isn't just code b it's concrete, copper, and really expensive electricity bills (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/technology/ecodatacenter-secures-600-million-euros-expand-ai-data-centres-2025-09-09/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


b= BlackRock Buys AI That Turns Sports Into TikToks

 * Minute Media acquired VideoVerse for $200-250M b an Indian startup that automatically creates sports highlights because humans
   are too slow at clipping goals AI is coming for sports media, and soon every touchdown will be auto-remixed into 47 different
   social formats* (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/09/blackrock-backed-minute-media-acquires-indian-ai-startup-that-extracts-sports-highlights/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p, OpenAI Employee Makes Movie With DALL-E, Calls It "Critterz"

 * An OpenAI staffer is making a full animated film using company tech for under $30M in 9 months, because Pixar's $200M budgets
   are apparently "inefficient."

 * If this works, Disney's animation department might want to update their LinkedIn profiles. (source)
   [https://www.engadget.com/ai/openai-tech-to-be-used-to-in-a-full-length-animated-film-155921502.html?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p6 Sweden Solves AI Music Piracy With Actual Royalties

 * Sweden's STIM created the first legal license letting AI companies train on copyrighted music while actually paying artists.
   Revolutionary concept.

 * Finally, someone figured out how to let AI learn from music without turning every songwriter into an unpaid intern (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/media-telecom/sweden-launches-ai-music-licence-protect-songwriters-2025-09-09/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p$ Sam Altman Complains That Social Media Feels "Fake" Now

 * The CEO of the company that made AI writing indistinguishable from humans is shocked that social media now feels artificial.
   Chef's kiss* for self-awareness.

 * When the guy who built the bot apocalypse says "this feels too bot-y," we've officially jumped the shark. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/08/sam-altman-says-that-bots-are-making-social-media-feel-fake/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p Google's AI Search Finally Speaks More Than English

 * Google expanded AI Mode to Hindi, Japanese, Korean, and two other languages after keeping it English-only for six months like
   some kind of linguistic gatekeeping experiment.

 * Turns out the rest of the world also wants AI to hallucinate answers in their native languages. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/08/googles-ai-mode-adds-5-new-languages-including-hindi-japanese-and-korean/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p5 Startup Raises $20M to Put AI Cameras in Nursing Homes

 * Teton.ai [http://teton.ai/] got $20M to create "digital twins" of elderly care facilities using computer vision, which sounds
   dystopian but is probably better than the current system.

 * AI surveillance for grandma is either the future of healthcare or Black Mirror episode 47. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/technology/elderly-healthcare-ai-company-tetonai-raises-20-million-funding-2025-09-09/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


bo8 Nuclear Industry Discovers AI, Uses It for Paperwork

 * Nuclearn raised $10.5M to bring AI to nuclear power, but don't worry b they're just automating documentation, not letting
   ChatGPT control the reactor.

 * Even the most paranoid industry on Earth found a safe use for AI: making boring reports slightly less boring. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/09/nuclearn-gets-10-5m-to-help-the-nuclear-industry-embrace-ai/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

Dear friends,

There is now a path for China to surpass the U.S. in AI. Even though the U.S. is still ahead, China has tremendous momentum with its vibrant open-weights model ecosystem and aggressive moves in semiconductor design and manufacturing. In the startup world, we know momentum matters: Even if a company is small today, a high rate of growth compounded for a few years quickly becomes an unstoppable force. This is why a small, scrappy team with high growth can threaten even behemoths. While both the U.S. and China are behemoths, Chinaâ€™s hypercompetitive business landscape and rapid diffusion of knowledge give it tremendous momentum. The White Houseâ€™s AI Action Plan released last week, which explicitly champions open source (among other things), is a very positive step for the U.S., but by itself it wonâ€™t be sufficient to sustain the U.S. lead.

Now, AI isnâ€™t a single, monolithic technology, and different countries are ahead in different areas. For example, even before Generative AI, the U.S. had long been ahead in scaled cloud AI implementations, while China has long been ahead in surveillance technology. These translate to different advantages in economic growth as well as both soft and hard power. Even though nontechnical pundits talk about â€œthe race to AGIâ€ as if AGI were a discrete technology to be invented, the reality is that AI technology will progress continuously, and there is no single finish line (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MWdkQgckqtvW5t30pQ97BCrcW2XSKgS5zGNZ6N1CRsZx3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3pcW4wr56F7ZMqNdVyKWdG7rqKTbW3bHMjB3CwjvLW3vVL6f6jCVNNW7Xcs4f4qhz6JW40RRTG88RHVQVbT8Gl4Zdc5hW2zbB8G6fd2YlW835TLN3pXQ26N7dh1KJRwxCWVYR5Ls88B3qqW1MZPFK1rLK5NN7YNBK8bChk1W4-TlqQ21N_pRW21yR2T5RjRksW34LyDy2x2s9LW952V0y9hl9b3N6mGw0Wq3HqSW32zpRk6XZKnJW6S05VD8kvC2_W5bG2Q42wdGFzW19qhDb7RdkrHf1wgrM-04 ) . If a company or nation declares that it has achieved AGI, I expect that declaration to be less a technology milestone than a marketing milestone. A slight speed advantage in the Olympic 100m dash translates to a dramatic difference between winning a gold medal versus a silver medal. An advantage in AI prowess translates into a proportionate advantage in economic growth and national power; while the impact wonâ€™t be a binary one of either winning or losing everything, these advantages nonetheless matter.

- Qwen3-Coder: The team pretrained Qwen3-Coder on 7.5 trillion tokens, 70 percent of which were code. During RL, Qwen3-Coder learned to solve tasks that required multiple turns of tool use.

Performance: The authors compared Qwen3-235B-A22B-Instruct-2507 and Qwen3-235B-A22B-Thinking-2507 to both open and proprietary models across tasks that involved knowledge, reasoning, coding, and tool use. - Qwen3-235B-A22B-Thinking-2507 achieved the best performance on 7 of 23 benchmarks compared to other reasoning models, often behind o3 and Gemini-2.5 Pro and ahead of Claud 4 Opus with thinking mode turned on. column1: People With AI Friends Feel Worse
People who turn to chatbots for companionship show indications of lower self-reported well-being

column4: and colleagues at Stanford and Carnegie Mellon examined (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MWdkQgckqtvW5t30pQ97BCrcW2XSKgS5zGNZ6N1CRsZx3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3l-W5m1vyC8TCN6GW3whdbL2sTX_SW2VdXyN4RB79vVdvdRq1h7-whVqtB6J12zbrYW1RRpyt37bmYVW1snwjT6xNl6jN3rtZ52wy2sdVG_6G55PGT46VGyJrM4WszPRVkp0Gw3fr1SsW343wNN3X25QVN76GN9nhW6qkW3H_2Fr6Fb4XyW5ns7-M8ZJNFQW94fXQn6PPXSKW8S5HsH3X4Cv2VjHPXv7b2v36VDD2Mp8H1nspW4z138s68ffrgV5fLgs8FJH9-W1L7_PX5zTZklf61GLWd04 )  correlations between usersâ€™ chatbot usage and psychological health. The more frequently users chatted
column6: and went without human social relationships

column1: Key insight: Chatbot users may not report the subject matter of their conversations accurately
column2: but LLMs can identify and summarize topics in chat histories. This makes it possible to correlate the intensity and depth of chats with self-reported measures of well-being

column1: How it works: The authors surveyed 1
column2: 131 users of the chatbot service Character.AI
column3: which provides chatbots for purposes like roleplay
column8: 363 conversations with 244 participants who agreed to share their chat logs.

column1: - The authors gauged the usersâ€™ stated motivations for using chatbots versus their likely motivations. They asked the users to select one of the following motivations: productivity
column4: or companionship. They also asked them to describe freely why they used Character.AI. GPT-4o classified the descriptions of chatbot usage according to the four categories of motivation
column5: giving the authors a more nuanced view.

column2: including how long they conversed and how comfortable they felt disclosing sensitive personal information.
including how many close human relationships they had.
they asked questions to measure the usersâ€™ well-being based on six factors: satisfaction

column1: - LLaMA-3-70B summarized conversations and fed the summaries to TopicGPT (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/MWdkQgckqtvW5t30pQ97BCrcW2XSKgS5zGNZ6N1CRsZR3prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3l1W975Jvw1c5xDwW74Rvdj6f0ZCjW15cMVY6yK9VjW7smjzp1s09p-N4w2CVF7q6XTW5cJl975_YLgTW4m1Kv636JfySW3HjVxM4YP9shW6y6yhL2BQknfW3cgn868MN3QsW4l3rs06mdkQsW6cgmmS49J32jVX035g4YFrVqW1pqj0p9bYdzqW8bVhsB4mnSQkW1Y7Z_57s_0h9W14n6lr8wR2yCW72TPKf5Jf8LmVbmJK-589FSFW59fkGB4FXGrfN6MBxrs1xk_ZW25jfY59b2RgHW4-f5s54rFcVjW7HkdKr43sFKQf4FPn2-04 )
Results: The authors computed correlations among the various signals and the six measures of well-being. They found that most users turned to chatbots for companionship
column2: whether or not they selected companionship as a motivation for their chats. Furthermore
column3: reliance on chatbots for companionship indicated lower well-being.

column1: - 12 percent of users surveyed selected companionship as their primary reason for using Character.AI
column2: but 51 percent described their chatbot as a friend
column4: or romantic partner. The chat logs showed much higher use of chatbots as companions: 93 percent of users had at least one conversation that showed companion-like engagement
column5: 80 percent of chat sessions involved emotional and social support
column6: and 68 percent involved romantic or intimate roleplay.

column1: - Greater use of chatbots for companionship correlated with lower apparent well-being. This effect was strongest when companionship was the main reason given in the multiple-choice survey (-0.47 correlation with lower well-being
column4: and 1 indicates the highest correlation with greater well-being).

column2: but: The authors found a consistent correlation between chatbot companionship and lower well-being
column3: but they didnâ€™t establish causation. The data shows that people who sought companionship from chatbots likely struggled with loneliness or a lack of close social connections. It remains unclear whether loneliness caused the users to use chatbots for companionship or vice-versa
column4: or whether using chatbots relieved or exacerbated their loneliness.

Each year we pick a theme—in 2024 it was America’s powerhouse economy, in 2023 the dangerous economics of defending the homeland. This week we publish “Governments going broke”, an https://click.e.economist.com/?qs=379fc00ae8734bc8bff938cdb7e27d83a4185e6e0e292071d8f392c9d4c3c1a46bf22c3375e3f28b5cd7d625432629da3754d066c97b554d in-depth look at the looming threat posed by rich countries’ mounting debts. It is written by our economics editor, Henry Curr. He warns that the world could end up with a nasty bout of inflation. Our https://click.e.economist.com/?qs=379fc00ae8734bc8dc4dae3303ebc500ffa22129d6c8cfb1ec77278b2971fd5dcafbe6a336c8324bad29ff40785cd1f2d2c6a5f5ce81fdb7 cover leader picks up the theme. Rich-world public debt is already worth 110% of GDP. Barring the covid-19 pandemic, it has not been this high since the Napoleonic wars. Governments will struggle to find a way out of the trap they have made for themselves. They cannot avoid rising interest bills or spending more on defence. Ageing populations exert an irresistible electoral pressure to hand over more cash. Raising taxes is just as hard. Many European governments already tax to the max; in America higher taxes are a ticket to electoral defeat. You might hope that productivity growth, powered by artificial intelligence, would come to the rescue. Sadly, pensions and health-care spending tend to rise with incomes: in big welfare states they will surge along with productivity. So too will interest rates, offsetting the fiscal windfall that comes from faster growth. It is therefore worth reflecting while there is still time on the grave harm inflation does to economies and societies. Uncontrolled inflation shifts wealth from creditors to debtors; from those with cash and bonds to those who own real assets such as houses; and from those who agree on contracts and wages in cash terms to those wily enough to anticipate higher prices. Inflation punishes the middle class and frays the social contract. Be warned. I spoke with Henry about whether a reckoning awaits America’s economy in this week’s episode of The Insider, The Economist’s new show. Also joining me were John Prideaux, our US editor, and our editor-in-chief, Zanny Minton Beddoes. Biggest Red Flags in SQL Courses
Yâ€™allâ€¦ Iâ€™ve seen some crappy and low effort (half-baked) SQL courses out there and I want to share what you should look out for and avoid. Choosing the wrong course can cost you TIME and MONEY! Which we donâ€™t wanna do when weâ€™re looking for a new, high-paying job ASAP! 
Here are the BIGGEST red flags:
If youâ€™re here, click this link to help me out w/ my newsletter metrics: WOOOOO [ https://substack.com/redirect/b4bfe53c-3c59-4053-912d-95d7a981cebe?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]ðŸ”—
Lack of instructor credibility 
Never buy a course without looking into the companyâ€™s or creatorâ€™s credibility. Of course a big company like Google has major credibility for their courses, but ther2e are many advantages of purchasing a course from an individual creator (like having a real connection with the instructor, transparency, realism, and behind the scenes insights that you might not get from a big box company like Google). However, many creators are â€œinfluencersâ€ without having the credibility to stand on. Many have only worked in the field for 1-2 years (or even 2-3 months), and theyâ€™re already pretending to be experts selling you courses to profit off you. If they havenâ€™t done it successfully themselves, donâ€™t believe them. Research the course creator on LinkedIn, look at their work history, and education so you can accurately assess their credibility before spending your money on a course. 
No emphasis on business problems 
Many SQL courses were created by laziness (or AI LOL). Basic â€œselect * from tableâ€ and filtering data for no reason. Do X, Y, Zâ€¦ blah blah blah! Then you get to interviews and on the job and realize you donâ€™t even know how to use it in the real world and solve real business problems. This lack of real world application can leave learners frustrated, confused, and with more questions than when they started. A good SQL course is not only going to teach you the topics, but itâ€™ll also guide you in applying them to realistic business problems so youâ€™re job ready. If the instructor doesnâ€™t do this, theyâ€™re either lazy or donâ€™t know how to (sorry I had to say it LOL).
Overall value (cost to depth ratio)
Sometimes a bargain SQL course can serve its purpose, but if youâ€™re gonna pay a good chunk of change for one, make sure the value is worth the cost. Are they only offering the basics and an intro for a high price? Or are they offering high-value learning, job prep resources (like portfolio help), and a community too? These are all things you have to consider when purchasing a course especially if youâ€™re spending money!
Donâ€™t fall into these traps, and choose a reputable course from a reputable instructor!
